The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Nation | Heat claims two polling officials
                                                                                                               Heat claims two polling officials
          OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT                              
	Bhubaneswar, April 23: The heat wave-like condition in the state claimed two polling officials who allegedly died of sunstroke while two others fell ill in Mayurbhanj and Keonjhar.        
	According to reports, Pabitra Mohan Muduli, of booth number-190 of Udala Assembly segment of Mayurbhanj, was hospitalised late last night allegedly due to sunstroke. He passed away at 11.15am today. Mayurbhanj collector S.K. Vashisth said Muduli was a reserve official. The cause of his death is being examined. Mayurbhanj recorded a day temperature of 44 degrees Celsius yesterday, Met officials said.        
	Another official, S. Mohanty died at Ghasipura in Keonjhar allegedly due to sunstroke. Yesterdays temperature at Kepnjhar was 43 degrees Celsius. Meanwhile, two officials of Udala Assembly segment, Rahim Khilar and Dambarudhar Mahanta were taken ill and were hospitalised.         
	Talking to The Telegraph, director S.C. Sahoo of the Met office said the condition was likely to continue for the next 24 hours. An official at the disaster management said only one death (in 32) was confirmed as a sunstroke.                                                                                                                                                                           
